<div id="descriptionContainer">
  
      <div id="description" class="readable stacked" style="right:0">
        
<span id="freeTextContainer17023776740620914378"><i>The Book of Lost Tales 1</i> stands at the beginning of the entire conception of Middle-earth and Valinor. Embedded in English legend and English association, they were set in the narratve frame of a great westward voyage over the Ocean by a mariner named Eriol (or Ælfwine) to Tol Eressëa, the Lonely Isle, where Elves dwelt; from them he learned their true story, the <i>Lost Tale</i></span>
  <span id="freeText17023776740620914378" style="display:none"><i>The Book of Lost Tales 1</i> stands at the beginning of the entire conception of Middle-earth and Valinor. Embedded in English legend and English association, they were set in the narratve frame of a great westward voyage over the Ocean by a mariner named Eriol (or Ælfwine) to Tol Eressëa, the Lonely Isle, where Elves dwelt; from them he learned their true story, the <i>Lost Tales of Elfinesse</i>. In the <i>Tales</i> are found the earliest accounts and original ideas of Gods and Elves; Dwarves and Orcs; the Silmarils and the Two Trees of Valinor; Nargothrond and Gondolin; and the geography and cosmology of the invented world.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17023776740620914378" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

