<div id="review_186696388" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/186696388" />
    <a title="Tori" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5839920-tori"><img alt="Tori" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/186696388?book_show_action=true">Jul 20, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tori" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tori" href="/user/show/5839920-tori">Tori</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer186696388" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15482746806527234409">If you are even a little bit curious about the history of Middle Earth, this is an essential volume. This, along with part 2, elucidate some of the more obscure mythological beginnings of Arda. The commentary section at the end of each &apos;chapter&apos; is very enlightening both linguistically and in terms of the development of certain motifs that crop up in Tolkien&apos;s works.<br/>I would suggest reading this after The Silmarillion (which is considered the polished product of the tales in these volumes). It ma</span>
  <span id="freeText15482746806527234409" style="display:none">If you are even a little bit curious about the history of Middle Earth, this is an essential volume. This, along with part 2, elucidate some of the more obscure mythological beginnings of Arda. The commentary section at the end of each 'chapter' is very enlightening both linguistically and in terms of the development of certain motifs that crop up in Tolkien's works.<br />I would suggest reading this after The Silmarillion (which is considered the polished product of the tales in these volumes). It may seem repetitive, but it is fascinating to see where these stories started and ended. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15482746806527234409" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

